The error says it all. You can't modify a list you are iterating. So, you have to use another list and write `numbers.remove(n)` in another place. That will work. Like so:
    import java.util.ArrayList;
    import java.util.List;
    public class Main {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            List<Integer> numbers = new ArrayList<>();
            List<Integer> deletions = new ArrayList<>();
            numbers.add(1);
            numbers.add(2);
            numbers.add(3);
            numbers.add(4);
            numbers.add(5);
            for (Integer n : numbers) {
                if (n % 2 == 0) {
                    deletions.add(n);
                }
            }
            for (Integer n : deletions) {
                numbers.remove(n);
            }
            System.out.println(numbers);
        }
    }
The error says :
> java.util.ConcurrentModificationException
because you modify your list in your loop. Modifying a list while iterating over it with a loop is not a good practice. The documentation says :
> it is _strongly recommended_ that you use a method that does not violate this policy.
You can also use `ArrayDeque` which is implemented as a circular array and which is thread safe and has no iterator.
You can use streams too:
